<section xml:id="s_poly_general" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Multivariate polynomial rings and monoid algebras</title>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_multi_poly">
    <title>Multivariate polynomial rings</title>
    
    
    <activity xml:id="spec_poly_ring_multiple">
    <title>Multivariate polynomial rings</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m></usage>
      <description>multivariate polynomial ring over <m>R</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero commutative ring. We define the <term>polynomial ring in the indeterminates <m>x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n</m></term> recursively as follows: 
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>R[x_1]</m> is the usual polynomial ring in the indeterminate <m>x_1</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]=R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_{n-1}][x_n]</m> for all <m>n\geq 2</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    When wishing to make the indeterminates explicit, we will write <m>f(x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n)</m> for an element <m>f\in R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </activity>
    <p>
        The recursive definition of multivariable polynomial rings allows us to use proof by induction in many situations, as the following results illustrate. 
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="th_polynomial_UFDs">
    <title>Polynomial UFDs</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero commutative ring. For all positive integers <m>n</m>, <m>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m> is a unique factorization domain if and only if <m>R</m> is a unique factorization domain. 
    </p>
    <p>
        In particular, <m>\Z[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m> is a UFD for any positive integer <m>n</m>, as is <m>F[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m>, where <m>F</m> is any field. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        The proof is by induction on <m>n</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Base case: <m>n=1</m>. <xref ref="th_UFD_preservation"/> implies that if <m>R</m> is a UFD, then so is <m>R[x_1]</m>. Conversely, if <m>R[x_1]</m> is a UFD, it is easy to see that <m>R</m> is a UFD as well: using a degree argument, irreducible factorizations of an element <m>c\in R</m> corresponds bijectively to irreducible factorizations of the constant polynomial <m>f(x)=c</m> in <m>R[x]</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Induction step: let <m>n&gt; 1</m>, and assume the result is true for <m>n-1</m>. We have 
        <md>
            <mrow>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n] \text{ a UFD} \amp \iff R[x_1,\dots, x_{n-1}][x_n] \text{ a UFD}\amp (\text{def.})</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \iff R[x_1,\dots, x_{n-1}] \text{ a UFD} \amp (\text{base case}) </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \iff R \text{ a UFD} \amp (\text{induction})</mrow>
        </md>.
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <p>
         By definition, an element <m>f</m> of <m>R[x,y]=R[x][y]</m> is a formal expression of the form 
         <md>
            <mrow>f(x,y) \amp =\sum_{k=0}^n f_k(x)y^k=f_n(x)y^n+f_{n-1}(x)y^{n-1}+\cdots +f_1(x)y+f_0(x)</mrow>
         </md>.
         Since each <m>f_k(x)</m> is an <m>R</m>-linear combination of powers of <m>x</m>, after distributing <m>y^k</m> through <m>f_k(x)</m> for each <m>k</m> and then collecting like terms, we can rewrite <m>f</m> as an <m>R</m>-linear combination of monomials 
         <md>
            <mrow>f(x,y) \amp =\sum_{\boldi=(i_1,i_2)\in \Z_{\geq 0}^2}a_\boldi x^{i_1}y^{i_2} </mrow>
         </md>,
         where <m>a_\boldi=0</m> for all but finitely many <m>\boldi\in \Z_{\geq 0}^2</m>. We make this observation more precise and more general in <xref ref="prop_monomial_expansion"/>. Since the notation gets rather unwieldy as the number of indeterminates increases, we are well served by introducing some notation and terminology. 
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="d_monomials">
    <title>Monomials and multivariate indices</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>\boldx^{\boldi}</m></usage>
      <description>multivariate monomial notation</description>
    </notation>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>\N</m></usage>
      <description>the natural numbers <m>\Z_{\geq 0}</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero commutative ring, and let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. A <term>monomial</term> of <m>S=R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m> is an element of <m>S</m> of the form <m>x_1^{i_1}x_2^{i_2}\cdots x_{n}^{i_n}</m>, where <m>i_k\in \Z_{\geq 0}</m> for all <m>k</m>. The tuple <m>\boldi=(i_1,i_2,\dots, i_n)</m> is called the <term>multidegree</term> of the monomial.
    </p>
    <p>
        To ease notation we adopt the following conventions. 
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\N=\Z_{\geq 0}</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We write <m>R[\boldx]</m> for <m>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m> and <m>f(\boldx)</m> for <m>f(x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Given any <m>\boldi=(i_1,i_2,\dots, i_n)\in \N^n</m>, we define <m>\boldx^\boldi</m> as  
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \boldx^{\boldi}\amp =x_1^{i_1}x_2^{i_2}\cdots x_{n}^{i_n}\in R[\boldx] </mrow>
                    </md>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Similarly, if <m>T</m> is any ring, and <m>\boldt=(t_1,t_2,\dots, t_n)\in T^n</m> any tuple of elements of <m>T</m>, given any <m>\boldi=(i_1,i_2,\dots, i_n)\in \N^n</m>, we define <m>\boldt^\boldi</m> as 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\boldt^\boldi\amp =t_1^{i_1}t_2^{i_2}\cdots t_{n}^{i_n} \in T</mrow>
                    </md>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        With this terminology and notation place, we can now give a precise description of monomial expansion in multivariate polynomial rings. 
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop_monomial_expansion">
        <title>Monomial expansion</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero commutative ring, and let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. Every polynomial <m>f\in R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m> can be written in the form
                <md number="yes">
                    <mrow xml:id="eq_monomial_expansion"> f(\boldx) \amp = \sum_{\boldi\in \N^n} a_\boldi\, \boldx^\boldi </mrow>
                </md>,
                where <m>a_\boldi\in R</m> for all <m>\boldi\in \N^n</m>, and <m>a_\boldi=0</m> for all but finitely many indices <m>\boldi</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Moreover, this representation is unique in the following sense: if 
                <md>
                    <mrow>f(\boldx) \amp =\sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}a_\boldi \boldx^\boldi \amp f(\boldx)\amp = \sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}b_\boldi \boldx^\boldi</mrow>
                </md>,
                are monomial expansions as in <xref ref="eq_monomial_expansion"/>, then <m>a_\boldi=b_\boldi</m> for all <m>\boldi\in \N^n</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                The proof is by induction on <m>n</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Base step: <m>n=1</m>. The statement in this case is just a reformulation of the definition of <m>R[x_1]</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Induction step: assume <m>n&gt; 1</m> and that the statement holds for all polynomial rings in <m>n-1</m> variables. 
                By definition, an element <m>f\in R[\boldx]=(R[x_1,\dots, x_{n-1}][x_n]</m> can be expressed in the form 
                <md>
                    <mrow>f \amp = \sum_{k=0}^{m}f_k(x_1,x_2,\dots, x_{n-1})x^k</mrow>
                </md>, 
                where <m>f_k\in R[x_1,\dots, x_{n-1}]</m>. By induction, for each <m>k</m> we have
                <md number="no">
                    <mrow>f_k \amp = \sum_{\boldi\in \N^{n-1}}a_{k,\boldi}\, x_1^{i_1}x_2^{i_2}\cdots x_{n-1}^{i_{n-1}} \amp (\boldi=(i_1,\dots, i_{n-1}))</mrow>
                </md>, 
                and thus 
                <md number="no">
                    <mrow>f_k(x_1,x_2,\dots, x_{n-1})x_n^n \amp = \sum_{\boldi\in \N^{n-1}}a_{k,\boldi}\, x_1^{i_1}x_2^{i_2}\cdots x_{n-1}^{i_{n-1}}x_n^k</mrow>
                </md>.
                Summing the terms <m>f_k x_n^k</m> yields a monomial expansion of <m>f</m> as described in the statement of the proposition. We now show that this expansion is unique. Suppose we have monomial expansions
                <md>
                    <mrow>f(\boldx) \amp =\sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}a_\boldi\, \boldx^\boldi = \sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}b_\boldi\, \boldx^\boldi </mrow>
                </md>.
                For each <m>\boldi=(i_1,i_2,\dots, i_n)\in \N^n</m>, let <m>\boldi(n-1)=(i_1,i_2,\dots, i_{m-1})</m>, let <m>\boldi(n)=i_n</m>, and let <m>\boldx^{\boldi(n-1)}=x_1^{i_1}\cdots x_{n-1}^{i_{n-1}}</m>. We have 
                <md>
                    <mrow> f=\sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}a_\boldi\, \boldx^\boldi \amp = \sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}a_\boldi\, \boldx^{\boldi(n-1)}x_n^{\boldi(n)} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \sum_{k\in \N}\left(\sum_{\substack{\boldi\in \N^n\\ \boldi(n)=k}}a_\boldi\,\boldx^{\boldi(n-1)}\right)x_n^k</mrow>
                </md>,
                and similarly 
                <md>
                    <mrow> f=\sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}b_\boldi\, \boldx^\boldi \amp = \sum_{k\in \N}\left(\sum_{\substack{\boldi\in \N^n\\ \boldi(n)=k}}b_\boldi\,\boldx^{\boldi(n-1)}\right)x_n^k</mrow>
                </md>.
                By definition of <m>R[x_1,\dots, x_{n-1}][x_n]</m>, and in particular corresponding notion of equality in this ring, we conclude that 
                <md>
                    <mrow> \sum_{\substack{\boldi\in \N^n\\ \boldi(n)=k}}a_\boldi\,\boldx^{\boldi(n-1)}=\sum_{\substack{\boldi\in \N^n\\ \boldi(n)=k}}b_\boldi\,\boldx^{\boldi(n-1)} </mrow>
                </md>.
                Since the line above is an equality of monomial expansions in the ring <m>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_{n-1}]</m>, the induction hypothesis implies <m>a_\boldi=b\boldi</m> for all <m>k\in \N</m> and all  <m>\boldi\in \N^n</m> satisfying <m>\boldi(n)=k</m>. But for all <m>\boldi\in \N^n</m>, there is a <m>k\in \N</m> such that <m>\boldi(n)=k</m>. Thus <m>a_\boldi=b_\boldi</m> for all <m>\boldi\in \N</m>, as desired.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>
    <p>
        The monomial expansion description of elements of a multivariate polynomial ring <m>R[\boldx]</m> allows us to give a complete and concrete description of all ring homomorphisms from <m>R[\boldx]</m>. The proof, on the other hand, will use induction once again. 
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="th_map_prop_multi_poly">
    <title>Homomorphisms from <m>R[\boldx]</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero commutative ring, let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, and let <m>R[\boldx]=R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m>. A ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R[\boldx]\rightarrow T</m> is uniquely determine by its restriction <m>\phi\vert_R</m> to <m>R</m> (considered as a subring of <m>R[\boldx]</m>) and the tuple of images <m>\boldt=(\phi(x_1),\phi(x_2), \dots, \phi(x_n))\in T^n</m>. Conversely, given a pair <m>(\psi, \boldt)</m>, where <m>\psi\colon R\rightarrow T</m> is a ring homomorphism and <m>\boldt=(t_1,t_2,\dots, t_n)\in T^n</m>, the map 
    <md>
        <mrow>\phi\colon R[\boldx] \amp \rightarrow T</mrow>
        <mrow>f=\sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}a_\boldi\, \boldx^{\boldi} \amp \mapsto \sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}\psi(a_\boldi)\, \boldt^\boldi</mrow>
    </md> 
    is a ring homomorphism. As a result, we have a bijection between <m>\Hom(R[\boldx], T)</m> and <m>\Hom(R,T)\times T^n</m>, described as follows. 
    </p>
    <image xml:id="im_multi_poly_ring_homo" width="75%">
                <shortdescription>Description of multivariate polynomial ring homomorphisms</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                \Hom(R[\boldx],T) \arrow[r,leftrightarrow] \amp \Hom(R,T)\times T^n \\
                \phi \arrow[r,mapsto] \amp (\phi\vert_R, (\phi(x_i))_{i=1}^n) \\
                \phi(\sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}a_\boldi\boldx^\boldi)=\sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}\psi(a_\boldi)\boldt^\boldi \amp (\psi, \boldt) \arrow[l,mapsto]
                \end{tikzcd}
                </latex-image>
    </image>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        Left as an exercise. Use a proof by induction along the lines used in the proofs for the two results above. 
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>

    <definition xml:id="d_noetherian_ring">
    <title>Noetherian ring</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    A commutative ring <m>R</m> is <term>Noetherian</term> if every ideal of <m>R</m> is finitely generated. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <theorem xml:id="th_hilbert_basis_theorem">
    <title>Hilbert's basis theorem</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    If <m>R</m> is a Noetherian ring, then so is <m>R[x]</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        It is clear that the zero ideal <m>I=(0)</m> is finitely generated. Let <m>I</m> be any nonzero ideal <m>I</m>. Define the following subsets of <m>R</m>: 
        <md number="yes">
            <mrow>L(I) \amp = \{0\}\cup\{a\in R\mid a \text{ is leading term of some } f\in I\}</mrow>
            <mrow>L_d(I) \amp =\{0\}\cup\{a\in R\mid a \text{ is leading term of some } f\in I, \deg f=d\}</mrow>
        </md>.
        It is straightforward to show the sets <m>L</m> and <m>L_d</m> are in fact ideals of <m>R</m>. The general idea used for both cases is the following: if <m>a</m> is the leading coefficient of <m>f\in I</m> and <m>b</m> is the leading coefficient of <m>g\in I</m>, then <m>a+b</m> is either equal to zero, or is the leading coefficient of <m>f+g\in I</m>; and <m>ra</m> is either equal to zero, or is the leading coefficient of <m>rf\in I</m> for any <m>r\in R</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        By assumption, <m>R</m> is Noetherian. Thus we have <m>I=(a_1,a_2,\dots, a_n)</m>, where <m>a_i</m> is the leading term of some polynomial <m>f_i\in I</m>.  for some polynomials <m>f_k\in R[x]</m>. Let <m>m=\max\{\deg f_1,\deg f_2,\dots, \deg f_n\}</m>, and let <m>J=\sum_{d=0}^m I_d</m>. Again, since <m>R</m> is Noetherian, <m>J=(</m>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <corollary xml:id="cor_hilbert_basis_theorem">
        <title>Noetherian polynomial rings</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. If <m>R</m> is a Noetherian ring, then so is <m>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>

    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_degree_multivariate">
    <title>Degree functions</title>
    <p>
         For general multivariate polynomial rings, there are a number of different ways to define a notion of degree. One of these comes automatically from our recursive definition: since <m>R[\boldx]=R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_{n-1}][x_n]</m>, given <m>f\in R[\boldx]</m>, we can define its degree with respect to <m>x_n</m> as its degree as a polynomial in <m>x_n</m> with coefficients in <m>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_{n-1}]</m>. More generally, given any one of the indeterminates <m>x_k</m>, we can define the <m>x_k</m>-degree of <m>f</m> to be its degree as a polynomial in the indeterminate <m>x_k</m> with coefficients in the ring <m>R[(x_i)_{i\ne j}]</m>. As is easily shown using the mapping property of multivariate polynomial rings, we have <m>R[\boldx]\cong R[(x_i)_{i\ne j}][x_j]</m>, where the isomorphism is given by the first natural map that comes to your mind. It follows that all the usual properties of degree functions of polynomial rings are ported over to the notion of <m>x_k</m>-degree. 
    </p>
    <example xml:id="eg_multi_poly_prime">
    <title>Prime ideal in <m>R[x,y]</m></title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be an integral domain. Prove that the ideal <m>(x^2-y^3)</m> is prime in <m>R[x,y]</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
        This notion of degree is strong enough to prove the following fact: if <m>F</m> is a field, then every ideal <m>I</m> of  <m>F[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m> is principal. 
    </p>
    
    
    
    <p>
         Another notion of degree is given by the so-called total degree of a polynomial. 
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="d_total_degree">
    <title>Total degree</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero commutative ring, and let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. The <term>total degree</term> of a monomial <m>\boldx^{\boldi}=x_1^{i_1}x_2^{i_2}\cdots x_n^{i_n}</m>, denoted <m>\deg \boldx^{\boldi}</m>, is defined as 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow xml:id="eq_tot_deg_monomial">\deg \boldx^{\boldi} \amp =\sum_{k=1}^ni_k</mrow>
    </md>.
    Given a nonzero polynomial , we define the <term>total degree</term> of <m>f</m> is maximum total degree of any monomial appearing in the monomial expansion of <m>f</m>: <ie/>, if <m>f=\sum_{\boldi\in \N^n}a_\boldi \boldx^{\boldi}</m>, then 
    <md>
        <mrow xml:id="eq_tot_deg">\deg f \amp = \max\{\deg \boldx^{\boldi}\mid a_\boldi\ne 0\} </mrow>
    </md>.
    Lastly, if <m>f=0</m>, we define <m>\deg f=-\infty</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        The total degree function on <m>R[\boldx]</m> satisfies some of the same properties of the usual degree function on a polynomial ring in one variable. 
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop_tot_deg">
        <title>Total degree</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero commutative ring, let <m>n</m> be a positive integer, and let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be nonzero elements of <m>R[x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n]</m>.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\deg fg\leq \deg f+\deg g</m>, with equality if <m>R</m> is an integral domain. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\deg (f+g)\leq \max\{\deg f, \deg g\}</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>
        Unfortunatley, one important difference between the total degree and the usual degree, is that when <m>n&gt; 1</m> the total degree function does not satisfy the division algorithm condition, as the next example illustrates. 
    </p>
    <example xml:id="eg_failure_div_alg">
