    <subsection xml:id="ss_monoid_algebras">
    <title>Monoid algebras</title>
    
    
    
    <definition xml:id="d_monoid">
    <title>Monoid</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    A <term>monoid</term> is a pair <m>(M,\cdot)</m>, where <m>M</m> is a nonempty set, and <m>\cdot \colon M\times M\rightarrow M</m> is an associative operation for which a multiplicate identity element <m>e\in M</m> exists: <ie/>, there is an element <m>e\in M</m> satisfying <m>e\cdot m=m\cdot e=m</m> for all <m>m\in M</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="eg_monoids">
    <title>Monoid examples</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Here are some familiar monoids: 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>(G,\cdot)</m>, where <m>G</m> is a group with respect to the operation <m>\cdot</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>(R,\cdot)</m>, where <m>R</m> is any ring and <m>\cdot</m> is the ring multiplication. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>(R-\{0\}, \cdot)</m>, where <m>R</m> is any integral domain and <m>\cdot</m> is the ring multiplication. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
               <m>(\mathbb{N}, +)</m>, where  <m>\mathbb{N}=\Z_{\geq 0}</m> and <m>+</m> is the usual addition. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>(\mathbb{N}^r, +)</m>, where addition is defined componentwise: <m>(a_i)_{i=1}^r+(b_i)_{i=1}^r=(a_i+b_i)_{i=1}^r</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>(\mathbb{N}^I, +)</m>, where <m>I</m> is any nonempty index set, and addition is defined componentwise: <m>(a_i)_{i\in I}+(b_i)_{i\in I}=(a_i+b_i)_{i\in I}</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>

    </example>
   <activity xml:id="spec_polynomials_in_monoid">
   <title>Monoid algebra</title>
   <statement>
   <p>
   Let <m>R</m> be a nonzero commutative ring, and let <m>(M, \cdot)</m> be a monoid. Define <m>R[M]</m> to be the set of all formal expressions 
   <md>
    <mrow>r \amp =\sum_{m\in M}r_m\, m</mrow>
   </md>
   where <m>r_m=0</m> for all but finitely many <m>m\in M</m>. We define binary operations <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m> on <m>R[M]</m> as follows: 
   <md number="yes">
    <mrow xml:id="eq_monoid_alg_add"> \sum_{m\in M}r_m\, m+\ \sum_{m\in M}s_m\, m \amp =\sum_{m\in M}(r_m+s_m)\, m</mrow>
    <mrow>\sum_{m\in M}r_m\, m \cdot \sum_{m\in M}s_m\, m \amp = \sum_{m\in M} t_m\, m \amp t_m=\sum_{\substack{m',m''\in M\\ m'\cdot m''=m}}r_{m'}s_{m''}</mrow>
   </md>.
   Note that the sum defining <m>t_m</m> is in fact finite, since only finitely many of the products <m>r_{m'}s_{m''}</m> are nonzero. The triple <m>(R[M], +, \cdot)</m> is a ring called the <term>monoid algebra</term> of <m>M</m> over <m>R</m>. 
   </p>
   </statement>
   </activity>
